          <msContents>
            <summary>
              <p>Single parchment folio, Shelfmark: HC.MS.03183; Qurʾānic Text: 24:12-16;  Lines per page: 10; Dimensions: 185 x 140 mm; Script style: kūfī, type D  V a; Estimated date of production: 800-1000. The manuscript has very few diacritics (and if only for letters <hi rend="italic">bāʾ</hi> and <hi rend="italic">nūn</hi>) and most of the the diacritics have been added later. The words <hi rend="italic">ḫairan </hi>(fol. 1r, line 1) and <hi rend="italic">fīmā </hi>(fol.  1r, line 10, this word is spelled as two separate word in the <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/index/index/sure/24/vers/14">Egyptian print of 1924, p. 458, line 12</ref>) seem to be written by the original pen. These diacritical dots appear in the shape of small strokes due to the sharp end of the calamus. On <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/handschriften/index/sure/24/vers/14/handschrift/1382/flip/1">fol. 1 verso</ref>, in line 1, the letter <hi rend="italic">bāʾ </hi>of the word <hi rend="italic">ʿaḏāb </hi>and the word <hi rend="italic">bihī </hi>(<ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/handschriften/index/sure/24/vers/14/handschrift/1382/flip/1">fol. 1v,</ref> line 5) seem to  have a diacritical dot below the letter written by  the original pen. <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/handschriften/index/sure/24/vers/14/handschrift/1382/flip/1">On fol. 1v</ref> in line 9: the word <hi rend="italic">lanā</hi> has a diacritical dot above the letter <hi rend="italic">nūn</hi>  written by the original pen. All other diacritics seem to have been  written by a different pen are not registered in the  transliteration. Vocalisation of the text is given by red and green dots. The basic reading is indicated by red dots, a secondary, alternative reading is marked sometimes by green dots, in the given fragment at four instances: (1) In Q 24:12 the word <hi rend="italic">ǧāʾū </hi>in line 2 of <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/handschriften/index/sure/24/vers/14/handschrift/1382">fol. 1r</ref> has a red dot above and a green dot below the letter <hi rend="italic">ǧīm</hi> of the word <hi rend="italic">ǧāʾū</hi>: Here the basic reading (red point) is <hi rend="italic">ǧāʾū</hi> the red dot signifying a vowel /a/, whereas the "green", secondary reading would be read as ǧēʾū meaning that the vowel /ā/ is pronounced toward an /i/, a phenomenon called <hi rend="italic">ʾimāla</hi> ("verbal inflexion [of the vowel /a/]") in the terminology of Qurʾān recitation. (2) On <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/handschriften/index/sure/24/vers/14/handschrift/1382/flip/1">fol. 1v</ref>, line 1, the word <hi rend="italic">fīhi </hi>has a red dot for the basic reading of the manuscript indicating <hi rend="italic">fīhi</hi>, the green dot after the letter <hi rend="italic">hāʾ </hi>signifies the vowel /u/ which means: <hi rend="italic">fīhu </hi>as variant reading (both variants, <hi rend="italic">fīhi </hi>and <hi rend="italic">fīhu</hi>, have no difference in meaning). (3) Another case where the green dots occur is on <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/handschriften/index/sure/24/vers/14/handschrift/1382/flip/1">fol. 1v</ref>, in line 2: The word <hi rend="italic">talaqqaunahū</hi> with green dots for the two vowels /a/ pointing most probably to the variant reading <hi rend="italic">talaqqaunahū</hi>.  For this word there are no red dots of the basic reading. The fact that  we find the indication of a reading by green dots may imply that the basic  reading of this manuscript was different from <hi rend="italic">talaqqaunahū</hi> (which is the reading of <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/lesarten/index/sure/24/vers/15">Ḥafṣ ʿan ʿĀṣim </ref>printed in the Egyptian print): For this verse (<ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/lesarten/index/sure/24/vers/15">Q 24:15) al-Farrāʾ (d. 822) in his work </ref><hi rend="italic"><ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/lesarten/index/sure/24/vers/15">Maʿānī al-Qurʾān</ref></hi> lists three variant readings, among them <hi rend="italic"><ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/lesarten/index/sure/24/vers/15">taliqūnahū</ref></hi><ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/lesarten/index/sure/24/vers/15">, a reading that is also listed by Ibn Ǧinnī's (d. 1002) in his </ref><hi rend="italic"><ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/lesarten/index/sure/24/vers/15">Muḥtasab</ref></hi>, a treatise of non-canonical readings. (4) In the same verse (Q 24:15) we find the word which consonants are <hi rend="italic">t-ḥ-s-b-w-n-h </hi>(if we interpret the letters as they are in the canonical text) on <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/handschriften/index/sure/24/vers/14/handschrift/1382">fol. 1r</ref>, in line 5. This word is marked by red and green dots: A red dot above the letter <hi rend="italic">sīn </hi>standing for the vowel /a/ point to the reading <hi rend="italic">taḥsabūnahū, </hi>a reading also known<hi rend="italic"> </hi>among the canonical readings (canonized by Ibn Muǧāhid's <hi rend="italic">Book of the Seven [Readings]), </hi>e.g.<hi rend="italic">, </hi>as reading of<hi rend="italic"> </hi>Ibn ʿĀmir (reference reader of Damascus), ʿĀṣim (Kūfa) and Ḥamza (Kūfa), whereas the four other canonical readers, <ref target="https://corpuscoranicum.de/lesarten/index/sure/24/vers/15">al-Kisāʾī (Kūfa), Nāfiʿ (Madina), Ibn Kaṯīr (Mekka) and Abū ʿAmr (Basra) </ref>read <hi rend="italic">wa-taḥsibūnahū</hi>.<hi rend="italic"> </hi> A verse separator for five verses in the shape of a small golden <hi rend="italic">hāʾ </hi>can  be seen in line 7 on fol. 1v. There are no verse seperators between  verses in the text (those marked by yellow color in the transliteration  are in the Cairo 1924 print).   The script style of the fragment is a kūfī script of the D group (cf. <ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/corpuscoranicum_pub/items/itemKey/KCAZQ5NS" sameAs="KCAZQ5NS" type="zotero">Déroche 1983, p. 41-45</ref>). Its vertical format is rather exceptional for kūfī manuscripts in script  style D.</p>
            </summary>
